defaultDfT research stated - defaultLower rail use defaultwasdefault a major source of benefits in having longer trailersdefault&#xa0;defaultBetween 27% to 32% of the environmental benefits of longer trail
defaulters are assumed to be gained by running fewer trains. By 2025 - 84% of the industry operational savings would be from lower rail costs. 
defaultThe assessment is very sensitive to the way that less rail traffic translates into fewer train kilometers and a realisti
defaultc picture would be of external costs rising significantly. Also, if trains were electrified or became quieter, the benefits of not running them would fall and so would the benefits of longer trailers. 
defaultLonger trailers would undermine low carbon energy-effidefaultcient raildefault, particularly the emerging supermarket (domestic intermodal) rail traffic, the sector with the highest growth potential of up to 12 
defaulttimes in a 25 year period 
default. Even the DfT figures states that the 2 metre trailer would reduce rail freight growt
defaulth by two thirds (down from 732% to 262%) by 2025. This is because the relative costs of road and rail will be adversely affected by the new units, and rail will face a cost disadvantage; savings of up to 15% are predicted by some in the road haulage indust
defaultry. However the DfT suggest that this impact would be offset by rail operator being able to use longer intermodal units than at present, increasing their own efficiencies.  However, this assumes that customers will want to invest in such units, ahead of in
defaultvesting in road fleet and also that the existing equipment, much of which is new, can be written off. All this is likely to result in a downward spiral for rail freight in this sector as critical mass is lost.
