defaultThe economic assumptions in the report are not realistic as they underestimate the extent to which longer vehicles will add to road mileage. 
defaultLonger trailers will be slower to negotiate road junctions and add to road defaultcongestiondefaultThe actual length of traffic lane occupied and the time that the lane is occupied needs to be fully taken into account. HGVs are considered to take up almost 4 times the space of an average car when stationery (passenger car units). Then one has
default to allow for the fact that HGVs are slower to negotiate junctions and need longer front and rear headway than cars as braking distances are greater.
defaultC  defaultWhat mechanisms are there for Government to increase investment in strategic roads and attract new investors. defaultAdefaultre there good examples from other countries that could be applied in the UK.default1. defaultDistance based lorry road user charging defaultFreight on Rail 
defaultsupports
default the principal of introducing a lorry road user charging system to ensure ensures fairer arrangements for the UK haulage industry. 
defaultAt present UK hauliers face unfair competition, with foreign hauliers not paying anything towards the costs of their use of U
defaultK roads. 
defaultHowever, we believe that the Government’s chosen time based system charges foreign hauliers too little, because of the EU restrictions, and 
defaultcould end up actually costing more in administration and enforcement than it raises. We believe that t
defaulthe Go
defaultvernment should instead have gone for a distance-based charging scheme, as most European countries are now doing. This would charge foreign lorries properly for using UK roads, and would raise revenue that could be used to fund a more efficient and greener
default UK freight industry. We therefore urge the Government to consider a comprehensive distance based system which could actually help reduce road congestion, emissions, accidents a
defaults well as raising revenue. 
defaultDisadvantages of the Time based system defaultbeing introddefaultuced next April 2014defaultGiven that foreign hauliers only account for 6% of UK vehicle miles, the administrative burden of this 
defaultscheme 
defaultboth for UK operators and DfT seems too high and could end up actually costing more in administration and enforcement than it
default raises.
defaultA simple but effective distance based  lorry road user charging scheme would therefore be fairer to UK hauliers but could also deliver wider objectives to:
default• Improve road safety
default• Reduce greenhouse gas emissions
default• Minimise the external costs from 
defaultheavy good vehicle traffic, including local air pollution, noise and congestion
default&#xa0;
defaultThe experience from Europe shows that lorry road user charging schemes can be introduced, that the technology is proven and that this delivers significant benefits, particular
defaultly to support the economy and reduce climate change – the two main objectives in the new Government’s transport policies.
default 
